  "original_title": "\u0b87\u0bb2\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0b9e\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bc1\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3 \u0baa\u0bc6\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0ba3 \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0bb5\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bc8 \u0baa\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0b9a\u0bc6\u0baf\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0ba4\u0bb1\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bc2\u0b9f \u0baa\u0bcb\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b95\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc8- \u0b89\u0bb2\u0b95 \u0b89\u0ba3\u0bb5\u0bc1 \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bae\u0bcd",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "The remaining petrol reserves in Sri Lanka are not even sufficient to meet normal needs - World Food Programme",
      "author": "Rajeeban",
      "body_lines": [
        "According to the World Food Programme, Sri Lanka's remaining petrol reserves are insufficient to meet even normal needs.",
        "Faced with severe shortages in fuel supply, the government has imposed restrictions on fuel imports for 12 months, the remaining petrol reserves are not even enough to meet normal needs, and this situation has affected all aspects of life, affecting people's ability to go to work, schools and government offices, the World Food Program noted.",
        "6.3 million people are food insecure in Sri Lanka and the situation is expected to worsen, according to the World Food Programme.",
        "The World Food Program has indicated that 6.7 million people do not eat acceptable food and 3.4 million people plan to provide emergency nutritious school meals.",
        "All food and consumables have become more burdensome. Due to this, people are buying small items and going to the market more often. It has been revealed through monitoring interviews related to the above market in June that the World Food Program has informed.",
        "According to the World Food Programme, the cost of nutritious foods and legumes has increased fivefold from the previous figure of $130 million."
      ],
